  "overview_metadata": {
    "overview_number": 1,
    "overview_title": "Four Is Better Than One",
    "overview_subtitle": "Extending the Coordinate Plane",
    "overview_description": "In this lesson, students extend the first quadrant of the coordinate plane to create the Cartesian coordinate plane. They identify, plot, and generalize the points located in each quadrant and points reflected across an axis. Students write an absolute value expression to calculate the distance between two horizontally or vertically aligned points on the coordinate plane."
  },
  "overview_items": [
    {
      "overview_item_type": "learning_goals",
      "overview_item_content_type": "html",
      "overview_item_title": "My Learning Goals",
      "overview_item_data": {
        "overview_item_data_type": "list",
        "overview_item_data_items": [
          "I can identify and plot ordered pairs of positive and negative rational numbers on the coordinate plane.",
          "I can use the signs of ordered pairs to identify which quadrant a point is in and to describe the symmetry of the coordinate plane.",
          "I can use absolute value to determine distances on the coordinate plane."
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "overview_item_type": "big_ideas",
      "overview_item_content_type": "text",
      "overview_item_title": "Big Idea",
      "overview_item_data": {
        "overview_item_data_type": "list",
        "overview_item_data_items": [
          "Distance and Direction",
          "Graphing Shapes",
          "The Number System"
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "overview_item_type": "essential_ideas",
      "overview_item_content_type": "html",
      "overview_item_title": "Essential Ideas",
      "overview_item_data": {
        "overview_item_data_type": "list",
        "overview_item_data_items": [
          "When you extend the <math><mi>x</mi></math>-axis and <math><mi>y</mi></math>-axis to include negative numbers, you create the Cartesian coordinate plane with four quadrants.",
          "The coordinates of an ordered pair denote the quadrant location.",
          "When one of the ordered pair's coordinates is zero, then the point lies on an axis.",
          "Ordered pairs that differ only by their signs are reflections across one or both axes.",
          "You can write and evaluate an absolute value expression to calculate the distance between pairs of points on a coordinate plane when they align horizontally or vertically."
        ]
      }
    },
